<h2>What QR Codes Actually Encode</h2>

<p>
  A QR code (Quick Response code) is a two-dimensional matrix barcode that encodes data as a pattern of black and white squares. The ISO/IEC 18004 standard defines the format. A QR code can encode up to approximately 4,296 alphanumeric characters or 2,953 bytes of binary data, though practical sizes are much smaller for reliable scanning.
</p>

<pre><code>{codeQrStructure}</code></pre>

<p>
  The QR standard is type-agnostic — it encodes a string. The "type" (URL, Wi-Fi, vCard) is just a convention on what string format the scanner app should interpret. Most smartphone cameras recognize these conventions automatically.
</p>

<h2>Common Use Cases</h2>

<h3>URLs and Landing Pages</h3>

<p>
  The simplest and most common use case. Encode a full URL (including <code>https://</code>) and the scanner opens it in the default browser. Best practices:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Use a URL shortener (Bitly, your own domain redirect) if the URL is long — shorter URLs produce less dense QR codes that scan faster.</li>
  <li>Add UTM parameters (<code>?utm_source=qr&amp;utm_medium=print</code>) so you can track QR code scans in Google Analytics.</li>
  <li>Test the URL before printing — a typo means a dead link on every printed material.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Wi-Fi Network Credentials</h3>

<p>
