</p>

<pre><code>{codeWifi}</code></pre>

<p>
  Note that this embeds your network password in the QR code. Only share this QR code in contexts where you'd share the password verbally anyway.
</p>

<h3>Business Cards and vCards</h3>

<p>
  A vCard QR code lets someone scan your business card and add your contact details to their phone instantly:
</p>

<pre><code>{codeVcard}</code></pre>

<p>
  vCard 3.0 is the most compatible format. iOS and Android both handle it natively. If you need more fields (LinkedIn, Twitter), include them as <code>X-SOCIALPROFILE</code> entries, though support varies.
</p>

<h3>Payments</h3>

<p>
  Payment apps use QR codes extensively. Venmo, Cash App, PayPal, and most cryptocurrency wallets generate scannable payment QR codes from their apps. If you're integrating QR payments into your own app, the format is payment-provider specific — check your provider's documentation for the exact string format.
</p>

<h2>Error Correction Levels: The Key to Reliable Scanning</h2>

<p>
  Every QR code includes redundant data so that it can still be decoded even if part of the code is damaged, obscured, or worn. The error correction level you choose determines how much of the code can be lost:
</p>

<pre><code>{codeErrorLevels}</code></pre>

<p>Key guidance:</p>

<ul>
  <li>For codes displayed on screens, <strong>M (medium)</strong> is fine — screens don't get dirty or torn.</li>
  <li>For printed materials (stickers, posters, packaging), use <strong>Q or H</strong> — they're more durable against wear and partial obstruction.</li>
  <li>If you're overlaying a logo in the center of the QR code, <strong>always use H</strong>. The logo covers roughly 25% of the code, which exactly matches H's recovery capacity.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Size and Quiet Zone Requirements</h2>

<p>
  QR codes have physical size requirements for reliable scanning:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Minimum size</strong>: 2 cm × 2 cm (0.8 inches) for codes scanned at arm's length. Larger for codes meant to be scanned from a distance.</li>
  <li><strong>Quiet zone</strong>: Every QR code requires a white border (quiet zone) of at least 4 module widths on all sides. Without it, scanners may fail to detect the code boundaries.</li>
  <li><strong>Resolution</strong>: For print, export at 300 DPI or higher. Our <a href="/tools/qr-code-generator">QR Code Generator</a> exports high-resolution SVG and PNG suitable for print.</li>
  <li><strong>Contrast</strong>: Dark modules on a light background. Avoid low-contrast combinations — a 3:1 contrast ratio is the minimum; 5:1 or higher is recommended.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Customization: Colors and Logos</h2>

<p>
  Standard black-on-white QR codes are reliable, but branded QR codes with custom colors and logo overlays are increasingly common in marketing materials. Guidelines:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Keep dark modules dark and light modules light — even with colors, there must be sufficient contrast between the two states.</li>
  <li>The three finder patterns (the large squares in three corners) must remain visually distinct — don't round them or change their colors too dramatically.</li>
  <li>Logo overlays should cover no more than 30% of the code area and should always use <strong>error correction level H</strong>.</li>
  <li>Always test scan the final customized code from multiple angles and distances before printing.</li>
</ul>

